article.headline: Red-hot Fire deal Monarchs eighth straight defeat
article.linkText: Fire deny Monarchs, win team-record sixth straight
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- When Portland opened the season 0-4 and
struggling, they had excuses. New players, new offense, injuries
and a tough early schedule appeared too much for the Fire.

	   But after the Fire extended their team-record winning streak to
six games with a 74-69 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on
Sunday night, what came off as excuses a month ago now looks
accurate -- Portland is a talented team that went through some
growing pains.

	   DeMya Walker scored 15 points and Ukari Figgs added 12 as the
Fire (10-8) continued to show signs of mastering their new offense
and learning each other's tendencies.

	   During the six-game streak Portland has shot better than 40
percent in five games, and for the second game in a row shot over
50 percent.

	   "We have really learned to trust our teammates and make the
extra pass,'' Fire coach Linda Hargrove said. "I think we have a
lot of confidence in each other right now.''

	   Ruthie Bolton led all scorers with 21 points for the Monarchs
(2-14), who lost their eighth straight game -- one shy of the team
record -- and fell to 0-10 on the road. Tangela Smith added 11
points and 10 rebounds and Kedra Holland-Corn had 10 points.

	   "They came out really hot, shot the ball extremely well, got
good looks and made their open shots,'' Sacramento coach Maura
McHugh said. "Our defense was just really soft the first half.''

	   Portland blew the game open early, outscoring the Monarchs 14-4
in the first six minutes and reeling off a 15-2 run midway through
the first half to take a 45-26 halftime lead.

	   The Fire ended any thoughts of a Sacramento comeback with a 9-0
run early in the second half to go up by 26 points. The Monarchs
never mounted a serious threat after that.

	   "Playing a team like Portland -- that is hot, playing at home --
they're going to have a lot of things going their way,'' McHugh
said "They took advantage of that and they played well as a
team.''

	   Sacramento shot 35.5 percent, compared to the Fire's 52.8
percent. Stacey Thomas had six of Portland's 21 assists. The Fire
had 20 or more assists for the third game in a row.

	   "Coaches told us at the beginning that Sacramento is a very
good team, and hungry for a win,'' Walker said. "It's not like
they're playing awful, they're just not getting the wins. We
couldn't come in to this game and take them for granted.

	   "We came out with the mindset that we're not going to play
their record, we're going to play their team.''

	   The Fire placed second-year reserve forward LaQuanda Barksdale
on the injured list before the game, one day after she had surgery
on her fractured left middle finger.

	   Barksdale was hurt in practice June 5, but continued to play.

	   Doctors successfully inserted a pin in the finger to facilitate
healing Saturday, and Barksdale is expected to miss one to two weeks. She
will be re-evaluated July 12.

	   Portland activated center Jenny Mowe to replace Barksdale.

	   Sacramento's Ticha Penicheiro missed her eighth straight game
due to injury. Earlier Sunday, Penicheiro was voted a starter on
the Western Conference All-Star team.
